Introduction

Zahida encouraged me to include measures of diversity among the predictor variables. I will take the chance to expand the description of diversity estimates initated in 2020-02-27. Back then I built a maximum likelihood phylogenetic tree of the amplicons, following directions form Callahan et al. (2016). I want to use a tree to estimate phylogenetic diversities. But, because I changed the naming of amplicons since then, I will build the tree again, to make sure everything is compatible.

I loaded the taxonomy information from 2020-02-11, which includes the taxonomy assignment and the original abundance table, both using sequences as names.

Data preparation

Abundance data

The idea is to relate diversity measures early and late in life with life-history variables of isolines. Thus, it makes sense to collapse the different replicates of the same isoline and time point. I add up those abundances, to estimate one diversity index per isoline and age with all the information, instead of having to average a few measures later. This is the same processing I did on 2020-04-13.

On 2020-02-27, I also filtered amplicons (by abundance) before building the phylogenetic tree. I realize now it was a mistake to use total abundance and prevalence across early and late samples as filtering criteria. Clearly, amplicons in early samples should be filtered independently from amplicons in late samples.

On 2020-04-13, I used a very conservative filter for the redundancy analysis, because two samples had very low sequence counts in one time point. Then, including low abundance amplicons in the ordination would make the isolines where relative abundances could not be measured that low stick out. That is, I had to represent all isolines in the same space. Here, for the moment I just want to measure diversity. I think diversity measures will be more accurate if I relax those filters and let low abundance amplicons be counted. I can raise the bar later, if needed.

# Per isoline:
EA.prop <- t(apply(EA, 1, function(x) x / sum(x)))
LA.prop <- t(apply(LA, 1, function(x) x / sum(x)))

# Abundance per replicate:
Ar <- SeqTabNoChim
rm(SeqTabNoChim)
Ar.prop <- t(apply(Ar, 1, function(x) x/sum(x)))

# Data frame of amplicon traits, available for use with picante package.
Traits <- data.frame(
  EA.meanProp = apply(EA.prop, 2, mean),
  LA.meanProp = apply(LA.prop, 2, mean),
  EA.prevalence = colSums(EA > 0),
  LA.prevalence = colSums(LA > 0)
)

MinProp <- 1.0e-6
MinPrev <- 3

p1 <- ggplot(Traits, aes(x=EA.meanProp, y=EA.prevalence)) +
  geom_point(size=0.5) + scale_x_log10() + ggtitle('Early') +
  geom_vline(xintercept=MinProp, color='red') + geom_hline(yintercept=MinPrev, color='red')
p2 <- ggplot(Traits, aes(x=LA.meanProp, y=LA.prevalence)) +
  geom_point(size=0.5) + scale_x_log10() + ggtitle('Late') +
  geom_vline(xintercept=MinProp, color='red') + geom_hline(yintercept=MinPrev, color='red')
grid.arrange(p1, p2, nrow=1)

EA.filter <- Traits$EA.meanProp >= MinProp & Traits$EA.prevalence >= MinPrev
LA.filter <- Traits$LA.meanProp >= MinProp & Traits$LA.prevalence >= MinPrev

rm(p1,p2,MinProp,MinPrev)

Alignment

Aligning only filtered sequences:

if (file.exists('alignment.RData')) {
   load('alignment.RData')
} else {
   AmpFilt <- sort(colnames(EA)[EA.filter | LA.filter])
   # AmpFilt <- unique(c(colnames(EA)[EA.filter], colnames(LA)[LA.filter]))  # same.
   alignment <- AlignSeqs(RNAStringSet(dna[AmpFilt]))
   BrowseSeqs(alignment, htmlFile='alignment.html', openURL=FALSE)
   save(alignment, file='alignment.RData')
   # Forces removal of tree upon update of alignment:
   if (file.exists('fitGTR.RData')) file.remove('fitGTR.RData')
}

Phylogenetic tree

if (file.exists('fitGTR.RData')) {
   load('fitGTR.RData')
} else {
   library(phangorn)
   phang.align <- phyDat(as(DNAStringSet(alignment), "matrix"), type="DNA")
   dm <- dist.ml(phang.align)
   treeNJ <- NJ(dm) # Note, tip order != sequence order
   fit = pml(treeNJ, data=phang.align)

   fitGTR <- update(fit, k=4, inv=0.2)
   fitGTR <- optim.pml(fitGTR, model="GTR", optInv=TRUE, optGamma=TRUE,
                      rearrangement = "stochastic", control = pml.control(trace = 0))
   detach("package:phangorn", unload=TRUE) # avoids name clashes
   save(fitGTR, file='fitGTR.RData')
}

The tree object, of class phylo, is in fitGTR$tree. I am discovering the possibilities of the picante package. I will add taxonomy information to the Traits data frame, in case I use it later.

Diversity

Diversity measures can be analysed by replicate, rather than by isoline. We use better the information that way. But I need isoline-level measures of diversity as well, to correlate with life-history traits.

I exclude low abundance and low prevalence amplicons, according to the filter set up above. When working with individual replicates from both early and late time

## By isoline
#  ==========
#
# I make two d.f. and then bind them either by column or by row, to
# make the wide and long versions, for plotting.
Diversity.Early <- data.frame(
  isoline   = rownames(EA),
  PD.Early  = pd(EA[,EA.filter], fitGTR$tree, include.root = FALSE)[,1],
  SR.Early  = pd(EA[,EA.filter], fitGTR$tree, include.root = FALSE)[,2],
  Shannon.E = diversity(EA[,EA.filter], index='shannon'),
  Simpson.E = diversity(EA[,EA.filter], index='simpson'),
  SeqNum.E  = rowSums(EA[,EA.filter]),
  batch     = sapply(split(SampleData, SampleData$isoline),
                function(x) sum(x$seqrun == 2) / length(x$seqrun))
)

Diversity.Late <- data.frame(
  isoline   = rownames(LA),
  PD.Late   = pd(LA[,LA.filter], fitGTR$tree, include.root = FALSE)[,1],
  SR.Late   = pd(LA[,LA.filter], fitGTR$tree, include.root = FALSE)[,2],
  Shannon.L = diversity(LA[,LA.filter], index='shannon'),
  Simpson.L = diversity(LA[,LA.filter], index='simpson'),
  SeqNum.L  = rowSums(LA[,LA.filter]),
  batch     = sapply(split(SampleData, SampleData$isoline),
                function(x) sum(x$seqrun == 2) / length(x$seqrun))
)

DiverIso.wide <- cbind(Diversity.Early[,-7], Diversity.Late[,-1])

Species richness (SR.Early and SR.Late) is correlated with phylogenetic distance (PD.Early and PD.Late), but not with sequencing effort (SeqNum). Measures of diversity late in life are not visibly correlated with those early in life.

The plot above shows roughly an effect of age on diversity, that Pau Carazo had reported previously, using slightly different data (different amplicon filters, and indices estimated with a different package). What we didnât know is that the effect is so much more accused when using Faithâs phylogenetic diversity. In a model:

This indicates that not only there are fewer species (amplicon variants) late in life, but that the ones missing are quite diverse or spread phylogenetically. This matches the results from the differential abundance analysis performed on 2020-03-17. You can see it here. In that report there is a figure with the fold-change of the amplicons with significantly different abundance between early and late life. Amplicons are distributed in the plot according to genus and color-coded according to phylum. There are many more genera and phyla with negative than with positive change fold.

Among the amplicons with a significant fold change in 2020-03-17 there are several Acetobacter and some Lactobacillus.

Redundancy analysis

Much can be improved from the first redundancy analysis performed on 2020-04-13. Little variance in life-history traits could be explained by the main axes of variation in amplicon abundance. A wiser selection of explanatory variables could help compensate the noise and the high dimensionality in abundance data. I recall Pau Carazoâs multiple linear regression analyses were more successful than my redundancy analysis. He found some effects of two ordination axes of abundance data on two out of three principal components of life-history variable. Neither diversity (Simpson index) nor Lactobacillus to Acetobacter abundance ratio made any important contributions to Pauâs models.

z2 <- LA.prop[, MaxDifPerGenus[MaxDifPerGenus$log2FoldChange > 0, 'amplicon']]
z1 <- z1[, colnames(z1) %in% colnames(LA)[LA.filter]]
z2 <- z2[, colnames(z2) %in% colnames(LA)[LA.filter]]
colnames(z1) <- paste0('L', colnames(z1))
colnames(z2) <- paste0('L', colnames(z2))
Selected <- cbind(z1, z2)

Predictors <- as.data.frame(log10(Selected + 1.0e-07))
Predictors$PD.Early <- DiverIso.wide$PD.Early
Predictors$PD.Late  <- DiverIso.wide$PD.Late
Predictors$Simpson.E <- DiverIso.wide$Simpson.E
Predictors$Simpson.L <- DiverIso.wide$Simpson.L
batch <- sapply(split(SampleData, SampleData$isoline),
                function(x) sum(x$seqrun == 2) / length(x$seqrun))
all.equal(names(batch), rownames(Predictors))

Biodiversity and significant change, with PCA

# Use the amplicons in significant results (sigtab) as a filter for abundance data
F <- rownames(sigtab)
z1 <- EA.prop[,F]
z2 <- LA.prop[,F]
colnames(z1) <- paste0('E', colnames(z1))
colnames(z2) <- paste0('L', colnames(z1))
A <- cbind(z1,z2)
A.sq <- apply(A, 2, skewness)
B <- A[,abs(A.sq) <= 0.25]   # not transformed
C <- sqrt(A[,abs(A.sq) >  0.25 & abs(A.sq) <= 1.0])  # sqrt-transformed
D <- log10(A[,abs(A.sq) >  1.0] + 1.0e-07)   # log-transformed
colnames(C) <- paste0('sqrt.',colnames(C))
colnames(D) <- paste0('log.', colnames(D))
AT <- cbind(B,C,D)
AT <- AT[, abs(apply(AT,2,skewness)) < 2]
AT.cov <- cov.wt(AT)
AT.pca <- princomp(AT, covmat = AT.cov, scores = TRUE)
stopifnot(all.equal(rownames(AT.pca$scores), rownames(DiverIso.wide)))
Predictors <- cbind(DiverIso.wide[,c('PD.Early','PD.Late','Simpson.E','Simpson.L')],
                    AT.pca$scores[,1:17])
RDA0 <- lapply(LH.all, function(lh) rda(lh ~ Condition(batch),
                                        data = Predictors))
RDAX <- lapply(LH.all, function(lh) rda(lh ~ . + Condition(batch),
                                        data = Predictors))
RDAX.aov <- lapply(RDAX, anova)
sapply(RDAX.aov, function(x) x$'Pr(>F)'[1])

Conclusions

I tried different ways to select the amplicon abundance-related variables that could carry the most information about life history traits. Unfortunately, neither diversity measures nor several summaries of abundance data produced significant models at the global level. Before exploring further options, I want to summarize the attempts, because, I admit, the code above is far from clear.

  • First, PCA of roughly filtered relative abundances must contain too much noise: it is impossible a priori to know what components may be related to life-history traits, and an ad hoc selection of apparently significant components is bound to have false positive results.
  • Though phylogenetic diversity index is significantly different between early and late samples, it does not help explain life-history variables.
  • In an attempt to reduce the noise of the data, I added up abundances of amplicons of the same genus (or class), following the intuition that taxa may be functionally redundant. But taxa abundance did not improve our predictive power.
  • I also used results from the differential abundance analysis, motivated by the idea that amplicons that significantly change abundance from early to late life samples may be more correlated with life history traits. For the moment, I used only a few amplicons (one from each genera represented in the significant results), in an attempt to reduce the amount of variables without using PCA. But it was not enough. I also used PCA, and nothing.

The global test always fails, and then I have to build a model by successive addition or removal of terms. Even that only works if I relax the threshold p-values.

save(SampleData, EA, LA, EA.prop, LA.prop, Ar, Ar.prop, Traits, EA.filter, LA.filter, fitGTR, DiverIso.wide, DiverIso.long, DiverRep.long, sigtab, taxa, file='Diversity.RData')
